<h3>The Question</h3>
<p>
    A <a href="/blocks/">Menu block</a> — the ARIA <code>menu</code>/<code>menubar</code>/<code>menuitem</code>
    family for invoking <em>commands</em> (not committing values) — is named as a harvest candidate but has
    no design. This survey gathers web-platform and library prior art per design-first step&nbsp;1, so the trait
    selections for the three shapes, focus model, checkable items, submenus, and command invocation reuse
    platform vocabulary. It grounds the forks in <a href="/backlog/173-menu-menubar-block/">backlog&nbsp;#173</a>
    — and corrects two things the item got wrong: it claims menus <em>mandate</em> roving tabindex (APG permits
    both), and it omits separator/group semantics and the "menu button" double-home in the droplist roster.
</p>

<h3>Recommendation (to ratify in #173)</h3>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Fork A — command invocation = the new <code>command</code> intent (#016), not Action.</strong>
        A menu item invokes an action — the declarative surface of the <code>command</code> intent
        <a href="/backlog/016-gap-9-webcommands-project/">#016</a> resolved into existence (grounded on the
        now-Baseline <code>command</code>/<code>commandfor</code> + <code>CommandEvent</code>). The
        <a href="/intents/action/">Action Intent</a> owns visual <em>weight</em> and stays orthogonal. This is
        the one net-new dependency — sequence #016 before/with #173.</li>
    <li><strong>Fork B — roving focus is the menu default, fixed.</strong> APG permits roving <em>or</em>
        <code>aria-activedescendant</code>; WE chooses <strong>roving</strong> (the GUI-menu convention every
        library ships), overriding the droplist family's <code>virtual</code> default, as a fixed mechanic.</li>
    <li><strong>Fork C — one Menu block with a <code>shape</code> dimension</strong> (<code>menubar | menu |
        context</code>), not three blocks; orientation derives from shape.</li>
    <li><strong>Fork D — checkable items reuse <a href="/intents/selection/">Selection</a></strong> under a
        <code>checkable</code> trait (<code>single</code>→radio, <code>multiple</code>→checkbox); plain
        <code>menuitem</code> = <code>command</code> only.</li>
    <li><strong>Fork E — submenu nesting reuses <a href="/intents/disclosure/">Disclosure</a>, not the
        tree-select <code>hierarchy</code> intent</strong> — a submenu is a transient cascading popup, not a
        navigable data hierarchy.</li>
    <li><strong>Fork F (omitted) — separator &amp; group semantics</strong> are first-class APG roles; the Menu
        block owns them directly.</li>
    <li><strong>Fork G (item didn't notice) — "Menu button" is mis-filed in the droplist family</strong>
        (<code>blocks.json:21,36</code>); #173 should claim the menu-button trigger and demote the droplist
        entry.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Finding 1 — WAI-ARIA APG: roles, keyboard, and the focus model the item got wrong</h3>
<p>
    The <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/menubar/">APG Menu &amp; Menubar pattern</a> defines
    <code>menubar</code>, <code>menu</code>, <code>menuitem</code>, <code>menuitemcheckbox</code>
    (<code>aria-checked</code>), <code>menuitemradio</code> (within a <code>group</code>), <code>group</code>,
    and <code>separator</code> (non-focusable). The keyboard model is fully specified — Down/Up within a menu,
    Right/Left between menubar items and to open/close submenus, Enter to activate/open, Escape to close and
    <strong>return focus to the invoker</strong>, type-ahead, and Tab to move out and close all menus.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>The item's "menus mandate roving tabindex" premise is wrong.</strong> APG: <em>"The menu container
    has <code>tabindex</code> set to <code>-1</code> or <code>0</code> and <code>aria-activedescendant</code>
    set to the ID of the focused item…"</em> — i.e. roving tabindex <em>or</em> <code>aria-activedescendant</code>
    are both acceptable, with <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/practices/keyboard-interface/">no
    menu-specific preference</a>. Roving is a library convention WE <em>chooses</em>, not a platform law
    (Fork&nbsp;B).
</p>

<h3>Finding 2 — native substrate (~June 2026): ARIA-composed, with two native seams</h3>
<ul>
    <li>The <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/menu"><code>&lt;menu&gt;</code>
        element</a> is a semantic alias for <code>&lt;ul&gt;</code> (no menu role, no keyboard); the old
        context-menu use is removed from the spec.</li>
    <li>Context-menu <code>type="context"</code> / the <code>contextmenu</code> attribute is
        <strong>dead</strong> — dropped ~2017, implemented by no browser
        (<a href="https://caniuse.com/menu">caniuse</a>). A context menu must listen for <code>contextmenu</code>
        and render a <code>role=menu</code>.</li>
    <li>The <strong>Popover API</strong> supplies the floating surface (Baseline; the Anchor intent composes it).</li>
    <li>The <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Invoker_Commands_API">Invoker Commands
        API</a> (<code>command</code>/<code>commandfor</code> + <code>CommandEvent</code>) is
        <strong>newly Baseline</strong> (Chrome&nbsp;135, Firefox&nbsp;144, Safari&nbsp;26.2). Built-ins cover
        popover/dialog; a menu item's action is a <em>custom</em> command (<code>--</code>-prefixed value →
        <code>CommandEvent</code>). This is the native substrate for the <code>command</code> intent (Fork&nbsp;A).</li>
</ul>
<p>So a WE menu is ARIA-composed, with native help only at the surface (Popover) and action-dispatch (Invoker
   Commands) seams.</p>

<h3>Finding 3 — every benchmark library separates Menu (invocation) from Select (value)</h3>
<p>
    Radix (<code>DropdownMenu</code>/<code>ContextMenu</code>/<code>Menubar</code>, roving tabindex), Headless UI
    (<em>"Menu… dropdown menus; Listbox tracks a selected value"</em>), MUI (<code>MenuItem onClick</code> vs
    <code>Select</code> value), Fluent (<code>MenuItemCheckbox</code>/<code>MenuItemRadio</code> first-class),
    Carbon (<em>"implements the APG menu pattern"</em>), Ant (<code>Menu</code> "executes the action" vs
    <code>Select</code> returns a value), and Shoelace (<code>sl-menu</code>, the lone line-blurrer) all keep
    menus distinct from form selects. Headless leaders use <strong>roving</strong> (Fork&nbsp;B);
    Fluent/Carbon/Radix make checkable items first-class (Fork&nbsp;D); Carbon/Ant parameterize one Menu by
    trigger while Radix ships three — the platform's shared role machinery favors one-block-with-shape (Fork&nbsp;C).
</p>

